: false, "mention": "ARE", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8753821849822998, "span": {"begin": 961, "end": 964}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1065, "end": 1067}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.4223276376724243, "span": {"begin": 1136, "end": 1141}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1212, "end": 1214}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6714"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "SRC proteins", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9919849634170532, "span": {"begin": 1298, "end": 1310}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1379, "end": 1381}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1406, "end": 1408}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:8811"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "pyrethroid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9987156391143799, "span": {"begin": 1465, "end": 1475}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:39353"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cypermethrin", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.8962560296058655, "span": {"begin": 1476, "end": 1488}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1524, "end": 1526}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1693, "end": 1695}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6714"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Src kinase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9926198720932007, "span": {"begin": 1732, "end": 1742}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5595"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "MAPK", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9563007354736328, "span": {"begin": 1755, "end": 1759}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5594"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ERK", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9937683343887329, "span": {"begin": 1760, "end": 1763}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5290"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PI3K", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.994968593120575, "span": {"begin": 1796, "end": 1800}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:207"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Akt", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9750772714614868, "span": {"begin": 1801, "end": 1804}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1824, "end": 1826}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1900, "end": 1902}}], "text": "This KE refers to decreased activation of the androgen receptor (AR) as occurring in complex biological systems such as tissues and organs in vivo. It is thus considered distinct from KEs describing either blocking of AR or decreased androgen synthesis.  The AR is a nuclear transcription factor with canonical AR activation regulated by the binding of the androgens such as testosterone or dihydrotestosterone (DHT). Thus, AR activation can be decreased by reduced levels of steroidal ligands (testosterone, DHT) or the presence of compounds interfering with ligand binding to the receptor (Davey &amp; Grossmann, 2016; Gao et al., 2005).  In the inactive state, AR is sequestered in the cytoplasm of cells by molecular chaperones. In the classical (genomic) AR signaling pathway, AR activation causes dissociation of the chaperones, AR dimerization&nbsp;and translocation to the nucleus to modulate gene expression. AR binds to the androgen response element (ARE)&nbsp;(Davey &amp; Grossmann, 2016; Gao et al., 2005). Notably, for transcriptional regulation, the AR is closely associated with other co-factors that may differ between cells, tissues, and life stages. In this way, the functional consequence of AR activation is cell- and tissue-specific. This dependency on co-factors such as the SRC proteins also means that stressors affecting recruitment of co-activators to AR can result in decreased AR activity (Heinlein &amp; Chang, 2002), as shown for the pyrethroid cypermethrin (Wang et al., 2016).  Ligand-bound AR may also associate with cytoplasmic and membrane-bound proteins to initiate cytoplasmic signaling pathways with other functions than the nuclear pathway. Non-genomic AR signaling includes association with Src kinase to activate MAPK/ERK signaling and activation of the PI3K/Akt pathway. Decreased AR activation may therefore be a decrease in the genomic and/or non-genomic AR signaling pathways (Leung &amp; Sadar, 2017).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:36:51 +0000 2026"}